SIMPLE: ster
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: -ster
<hw>-ster</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[OE. & AS. <ets>-estre</ets>,
<ets>-istre</ets>.]</ety> <def>A suffix denoting <xex>the agent</xex>
(originally a woman), especially a person who does something <xex>with
skill</xex> or <xex>as an occupation</xex>; as in spin<xex>ster</xex>
(originally, a woman who spins), song<xex>ster</xex>, ba<xex>xter</xex>
(= bake<xex>ster</xex>), young<xex>ster</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Brewing, baking, and weaving were formerly feminine
labors, and consequently <xex>brewster</xex>, <xex>baxter</xex>, and
<xex>webster</xex> meant, originally, the woman (not the man) who brews,
bakes, or weaves. When men began to perform these duties the feminine
appellations were retained.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stercobilin</ent>⟦br⟧
